Cc: Blitz-list <blitz-list%netsoc.ucd.ie@uk.ac.essex.mailhost>
Subject: 68030 bug? Nope.  (Was Re: GetaShape)
In-Reply-To: <yam7274.2775.1747190704@post.demon.co.uk>
Message-Id: <SIMEON.9712011424.A@fpgapc7.essex.ac.uk>
Date: Mon, 1 Dec 1997 14:47:24 +0000 (GMT)
Priority: NORMAL
X-Mailer: Simeon for Win32 Version 4.1.2 Build (32)
X-Authentication: IMSP
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; CHARSET=US-ASCII

Try the following:
If you have 60ns RAM, remove the jumper that makes the board operate in 
60ns mode. <<not very likely to have an effect

Disalbe Data Burst   <<MOST LIKELY PROBLEM
------------------

The probem might be this:

Writing and reading from chip mem with combination of blitter/cpu makes 
the cache go mad :/ 

NOW i know why I had that strange bug with my neural network.
I was using blitter Line to draw to a bitmap
Then using Point to read the data into an array. I guess point is a 
CPU-based routine.. so the cache does not get updated right away.
Or it *Does* get updated, but the data burst fetches data before they 
are written by the blitter (!) [i use a 4x4 pixel bitmap, :)]

About 68040.. this has bus-snooping so it can automatically update the 
cache if something else changes shared memory. I don't know if 
bus-snooping is activated on Amiga 68040 boards, but it should be

Hope this helps:):):)




Christos Dimitrakakis (aka Olethros)
Electronic Engineer,
Software Developer for the Amiga computer
University of Essex




@ENDNODE
