MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain;
	charset="US-ASCII"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable
X-Priority: 3
X-MSMail-Priority: Normal
X-Mailer: Microsoft Outlook Express 4.71.1008.3
X-MimeOle: Produced By Microsoft MimeOLE Engine V4.71.1008.3

Hi,

<snip>

>> I could develop it further, but I don't know if I have time or =
whether it's worth it, but you can have it anyway :)
>>
>Nah, better use PhxAss on its own.

But by using PhxAss, you can't access any external data, such as labels. =
  This is where a program like mine could come in.  One idea I had was =
that you could have a block of commented asm code.  Then you mark this =
text, run my program, and it would assemble it with PhxAss, taking into =
account any references to labels.   Like -=20

;  LEA table(pc),a0
;  MOVE.l (a0,d0.w*4),d1
;  MULU.l #233,d1

Then run my program, and you end up with some code you can INCBIN.  When =
you change it, just run the program again.  IMHO, that would be handy.

>and that double-indexed addressing is pretty slow, so don't use it :)
>Also, long mulu/s are slow (twice as slow as .w ones)!

They weren't supposed to be fast, they were just examples.  If you want =
to multiply a quick by an integer, a 32*32=3D32 bit multiply is faster =
than using word multiplies (with the quick in d0, it's just mulu.l =
#233,d0)

>Furthermore the 68060 does not support the MUL.l 32,32->64 format=20
>(mulu.l dx,dy:dz) so *never* use it, unless you make seperate 060=20
>version.

That instruction will be emulated by the 68060.library, so it works =
fine.  Though it is probably best to do different versions if possible.

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid







@ENDNODE
