On 04-Dec-97, Julian Kinraid wrote:
>Hi,

>I would avoid GetReg if possible.  Each time you call it, it pushes lots=
 of
>registers onto the stack, fetches the variable, then pulls the registers=
 back
>off the stack.

Yes if you use complex expressions in your getreg command.
but if you just use
getreg d0,a.l; it will most likely translated to code
move.loffset(Ax),d0

Where the OFFSET is the variables offset from the start of the variable s=
pace.
And Ax is the pointer to the data area.

I'm not absolutely sure of this because I don't like to disasm ANY higher=

language code. :)

>Using statements/functions are faster, and fastest of all is to write th=
em in
>a lib, as this avoids some of the code that statements/functions use.

Not if you use expressions as parameters!!!

>> BTW anybody knowing how the binary including is working??
>> Fast?
>> Reliable?
>> Easy to use?

>I haven't used it myself, but I would assume you just -

>bin:  INCBIN "data/code.bin"

>and just jump to bin: to execute that code.

So you think that it can handle the hunks in those code segments???

>> This because I could take some move16 to my C2P code too!!
>> And in some cases the FPU commands could be really big help!!

>If you're interested I've written a program that lets you type in an
>instruction, eg. mulu.l d0,d1:d2, and it will give you the data for that=

>command back, eg. DC.w $47c5.   It uses PhxAss, so any command that PhxA=
ss
>supports can be used, except using labels.  I have an idea on how to use=

>labels, but I don't know whether it's worthwile adding it.  It would let=
 you
>use commands like -
>jmp ([tabel,pc],d0.w*4)

>I could develop it further, but I don't know if I have time or whether i=
t's
>worth it, but you can have it anyway :)

It could be enough, because in blitz the special asm is quite rarely need=
ed.
For example I would use it to C2P routine to copy the data from fast to
chip. It would help in 040 and 060 code to compensate the sligth slower
chip speed compared to 030.

