X-MimeOle: Produced By Microsoft MimeOLE Engine V4.71.1008.3

Hi,

>>I would avoid GetReg if possible.  Each time you call it, it pushes =
lots of
>>registers onto the stack, fetches the variable, then pulls the =
registers back
>>off the stack.

>Yes if you use complex expressions in your getreg command.
>but if you just use
>getreg d0,a.l; it will most likely translated to code
>move.loffset(Ax),d0

Well, I'm afraid you're wrong.  A getreg d0,a.l _will_ produce something =
like -

MOVEM.l d1-d6/a0-a3,-(a7)
MOVE.l  offset(a4),d0
MOVEM.l (a7)+,d1-d6/a0-a3

It's a shame that Blitz doesn't optimise anything.
I asked RWE if they could write a fastgetreg that wouldn't bother with =
saving registers, but they didn't reply :(

>>Using statements/functions are faster, and fastest of all is to write =
them in
>>a lib, as this avoids some of the code that statements/functions use.

>Not if you use expressions as parameters!!!

How do you mean?

What i was saying is that statements/functions written in Blitz (not =
ones in libs) allocate some storage on the stack, and move the =
parameters into this storage, even if the whole procedure is in asm and =
doesn't use this storage.  Still faster than getreg, but if you write =
the procedures in a lib, you will avoid this code.

<snip>

>>bin:  INCBIN "data/code.bin"
>>and just jump to bin: to execute that code.

>So you think that it can handle the hunks in those code segments???

That's why it's called 'code.bin', not 'code.exe' :)

<snip>

>>I could develop it further, but I don't know if I have time or whether =
it's
>>worth it, but you can have it anyway :)

>It could be enough, because in blitz the special asm is quite rarely =
needed.
>For example I would use it to C2P routine to copy the data from fast to
>chip. It would help in 040 and 060 code to compensate the sligth slower
>chip speed compared to 030.

I might have another look at it, now that I have some time.

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid



@ENDNODE
