MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

On 10-Dec-97, Paul Burkey wrote:
>Hi Andrew,

>> Let me explain.  Im trying a new scrolling method that will 
>> continuously hardware scroll.  Because when the edge of a bitmap is 
>> reached, it actualy wraps around, but one pixel up.  If I just blit 
>> my background shapes one pixel down when this is reached you should 
>> have continuous hardware scroll (Its probably very system 
>> un-friendly, though!!! (sorry guys)).

>If your bitmap is a bit taller than it needs to be then there shouldn't
>be a problem. It's only unfriendly if your blitting into memory you
>don't own. If all your blitting is done to the bitmaps memory then
>theres no problems. I would imagine that any blitting that goes over
>the edge of your bitmap will appear on the other side +1 pixel down
>so if you're blitting to the verry bottom of your bitmap the 1 pixel
>down would take it into stray memory.

  I've done one, and all you need is your bitmap to be one pixel higher,
as after your've scrolled around once you can display your bitmap back
in its original position.

   The only problem that I have with this solution, is that although the
screen might look continuous, it can have both ends of the bitmap in the
centre of the screen- so if you have blits crossing this border, you
have to blit them at both ends of the bitmap, as they cross over. This
could be a problem if you have lots of blits onscreen, as these extra
blits might slow down your frame rate. Has anyone got around this
problem?
  It seems to me a trade-off, chip mem saved vs less objects
onscreen :-/
 
-- 
      Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
    



@ENDNODE
