To: Blitz List <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Date: Thu, 01 Jan 1998 22:58:46 -0000
Message-ID: <yam7305.2312.30548864@smtp.thenet.co.uk>
In-Reply-To: <199801010534.SAA18188@fep2-orange.clear.net.nz>
X-Mailer: YAM 1.3.5 [040] - Amiga Mailer by Marcel Beck
Subject: Re: Blitzy things ...
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

On 30-Dec-97, Julian Kinraid wrote:
<snip>
JK>It's a good idea in theory, but in practice it won't work.  How do you
JK>know which code you can discard?  There is no easy way Blitz will know
JK>which code is used by each command.

The compiler for Delphi automatically works out if a bit of code is never
going to be run in your program and leaves it out of the executable. I
have no idea how difficult this would be to do to Blitz, but it would be
very useful.

Delphi also warns you about redundant variables ( never used or given a
value that is never used, etc ). This would be useful in Blitz where if
you make a spelling mistake with a variable name, you can spend ages
trying to track down the problem.

JK>Even if there was some arcane way to do it, the time would we better
JK>spent coming up with a different library system.  A different library
JK>system also could get rid of the library numbers (solving a lot of
JK>hassle), and you would be able to have more than 256 libraries on one
JK>system.

A different library system would be best. Although without writing
libraries solely as functions, I don't know how you would get around the
problem of what to include and what not to include.

While we're on the subject, how about these as changes to Blitz:

Unsigned types. This is quite important ommission from Blitz. ( How about
my_var.ub ? )

SHARED supports wildcards for variable names. This would encourage the
use of structured variable nameing. e.g. SHARED GLOB_#? or SHARED CAR_#?
( although this could degenerate into just SHARED #? :)

ProtoStatement and ProtoFunction keywords to allow proper function
prototyping. It is quite annoying that because of having to
forward-declare everything, you cannot always have all your functions and
statements together, or in the most understandable order.

Constants can be strings. A minor point, but constants being limited to
numbers can be annoying occasionally.

Bye,
Alex

-- 
+-- Alex Wingrove / awingrove@thenet.co.uk --+

[      www.thenet.co.uk/~awingrove/blitz/       ]
[ Blitz Program Collection  and  Blitz List FAQ ]




@ENDNODE
