From: "Julian Kinraid" <jkinraid@clear.net.nz>
To: "Blitz List" <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Subject: Re: Blitzy things ...
Date: Fri, 2 Jan 1998 21:42:30 +1300
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain;
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable
X-Priority: 3
X-MSMail-Priority: Normal
X-Mailer: Microsoft Outlook Express 4.71.1008.3
X-MimeOle: Produced By Microsoft MimeOLE Engine V4.71.1008.3

Hi Alexander,

<snip>

>The compiler for Delphi automatically works out if a bit of code is =
never
>going to be run in your program and leaves it out of the executable. I
>have no idea how difficult this would be to do to Blitz, but it would =
be
>very useful.

Well, AFAIK, this is how it would have to be done -=20

A program uses functions x and y in a library.  Blitz starts scanning =
through the library code at the start of function x.  It traces all the =
branches (Bxx), JMPs, JSRs, until it gets to the last RTS.  It also =
traces all variable usage, so if one command uses a lot of data (DCB.l =
0,100), that data will only be included with that command.  Then it does =
this with function y.  So now Blitz knows all the stuff that it used and =
removes the rest.  Whether you understand this or not, it's basically a =
'hack' and prone to errors.

Now that I think about it, it's even harder.  If Blitz were to remove =
some code in the middle, offsets for a lot of stuff would have to be =
changed.  A complete waste of time IMHO.

>Delphi also warns you about redundant variables ( never used or given a
>value that is never used, etc ). This would be useful in Blitz where if
>you make a spelling mistake with a variable name, you can spend ages
>trying to track down the problem.

Yes, that would be a great help.

>JK>Even if there was some arcane way to do it, the time would we better
>JK>spent coming up with a different library system.  A different =
library
>JK>system also could get rid of the library numbers (solving a lot of
>JK>hassle), and you would be able to have more than 256 libraries on =
one
>JK>system.
>
>A different library system would be best. Although without writing
>libraries solely as functions, I don't know how you would get around =
the
>problem of what to include and what not to include.

Blitz should use a linker type of system.  AFAIK, this does exactly what =
we want.  Also, you could linker libs already available, such as =
amiga.lib and debug.lib on the Amiga Dev CD.  You could probably write =
libraries in any programming system that supports linking (eg. SAS C, =
PhxAss), and take advantage of all the optimising features that these =
programs have.

>While we're on the subject, how about these as changes to Blitz:
>
>Unsigned types. This is quite important ommission from Blitz. ( How =
about
>my_var.ub ? )

Definately.

>SHARED supports wildcards for variable names. This would encourage the
>use of structured variable nameing. e.g. SHARED GLOB_#? or SHARED =
CAR_#?
>( although this could degenerate into just SHARED #? :)

Support for global and static variables would be nice.

>ProtoStatement and ProtoFunction keywords to allow proper function
>prototyping. It is quite annoying that because of having to
>forward-declare everything, you cannot always have all your functions =
and
>statements together, or in the most understandable order.

Yes, Blitz should support this, as well as a lot of features other =
programs have.  This would make using stuff made for 'C' a lot easier.

>Constants can be strings. A minor point, but constants being limited to
>numbers can be annoying occasionally.

Yes, and perhaps floating point numbers.

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid




@ENDNODE
