  by orca.ucd.ie with SMTP; 29 Dec 1997 17:52:42 -0000
Received: from ah210@localhost by chebucto.ns.ca id <91162-13948>; Mon, 29 Dec 1997 13:56:36 -0400
Date:	Mon, 29 Dec 1997 13:56:29 -0400 (AST)
Sender: John Mason <ah210@chebucto.ns.ca>
From:	John Mason <ah210@chebucto.ns.ca>
To:	Tim Johnson <trilobyte@rockford.com>
cc:	Blitz-List <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Subject: Re: Changing titlebar of Screen or Window
In-Reply-To: <yam7302.2030.4502912@rockford.com>
Message-ID: <Pine.SUN.3.91.971229135015.5964B-100000@chebucto.ns.ca>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII


On Mon, 29 Dec 1997, Tim Johnson wrote:

> I'm writing a game where I would like to be able to print the score & tiles
> remaining
> to the titlebar of the window or screen that the game is running in.  Should I
> do
> this via a simple Print or is there a better (more system friendly?) way to do
> it?

Yes, there is.  I wrote a statement that will do this for you:

Statement setscrtitle{win,titleaddr.l}
  winaddr.l=Peek.l(Addr Window(win))
  result=SetWindowTitles_(winaddr.l,-1,titleaddr.l)
End Statement

This will set the title of the window win to the text at titleaddr.  For 
example, if I wanted to change the title of window 4, to "Hello there", I 
would do this:

  mytitle.s="Hello there"
  setscrtitle{4,&mytitle.s}

You can change this to edit a window's title as well as the screen's title
by replacing the -1 value in SetWindowTitles_() with a pointer to string 
for the window title, ie:

Statement setscrtitle{win,titleaddr.l}
  winaddr.l=Peek.l(Addr Window(win))
  result=SetWindowTitles_(-1,winaddr.l,titleaddr.l) ; no screen title, 
						    ; but a window title
End Statement

[....]

  wtitle.s="My window title"
  setscrtitle{4,&wtitle.s}
  
Hope this helps :)

	|      ///       John Mason           | 
	|     /// Amiga User Extraordinaire!  |  
	| \\\///    ah210@chebucto.ns.ca      |
	|  \XX/   A500 020+881 3.1 7MB RAM    | 
	|www.ccn.cs.dal.ca/~ah210/Profile.html|
			 




@ENDNODE
