On 19-Dec-97, C Dimitrakakis wrote:

> On Fri, 19 Dec 1997 12:05:25 EET-2 Kai Nikulainen =


> Yes, using a simple per-character encryption is not quite good enough..=

> since it is still possible to edit exe with a hex editor once you know
> that it is a simple mod-5-offset encoding.
> Best thing to do is to compress them, so that the final string that is =

> embedded in your .exe will have encryption applied to groups of =

> characters rather than single characters.

The best way would be to use say 128 byte table.

In your decode session you just add these numbers to your crypted text.
then you AND $ff to them. This just to cut the over byte size of and writ=
e it
with chr$ to the string you use. You can make it even harder, just by usi=
ng
different kind of offsets and so on for the different strings.


This next is an irrelevant add on, but still quite interesting.

Say that you and some other guy have identical copy of 40000 byte random
number table. Now if you use method that first char in the table is added=

with the first char in the crypted text and so on. You get number sequenc=
e
that CAN NOT be opened if you don't have the cryption table. Even if you =
use
table say 4000 bytes, you get so secured cryption that you can send 10
megabyte file via internet so that even any intelligent agency CAN'T
break it!!! This of course needs that the cryption table is known only yo=
u
and the recipient.


If the message or what ever you are sending is shorter than the cryption
table. The message is so safe, that without the cryption table NOBODY wil=
l
ever break it. This means that you can use millions or even trillions of
years of computer time and you just can't tell what the message is!!!
If you got the table you can get it in less than a second.

This method is used by intelligent agencies, because it's fully secured

