Subject: Re: CODING/DECODING
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

Hi Berhan,

> what I had in mind is a picture-shrinker!
> 1) for every picture do:
> 2) for every pixel(starting 0-319, 0-255) read color
> 3) if color(0) and color(1) are same index(0-255) then Colour=the colour
index
> of the pixel(s) and Number of  pixels=Number of pixels+1

This is the kind of thing I used o spend all my time working on. I
find this type of project to be much more interesting that writing
games! I spend many weeks developing picture compression that sounds
similar to your idea, text compression that was based on common words
and also language translation systems. I spent much time doing that
kind of thing and it was the happiest time I ever spent programming :)

My only advice to you is, go away and try out your ideas. The only
way you'll come up with somthing that is impresive is if you come up
with an idea that nobody has used before and possibly an idea that
nobody will understand! :) I can tell you that 99% of crazy ideas
don't work but when 1% of your ideas work it makes it worthwhile!
Theres no point in discussing untested ideas because you need to
learn from trial and error. One ay to avoid wasted time is to read
up on existing techniques because you may end up spending a month
reinventing the wheel.

> and since it is a text(ascii data) it would be packed quite well..

Interesting you say that. Ascii text does compress well because
it's only using a few bits out of th byte. Real ascii is only
7 bits but if you're talking about nubers and letters you'll be
left with just 6 bit of data used up out of a potential 8bits.
So of course this is going to compress well but you'll probably
end up with little benefit when compared to the outdated iff
sytem.

>From my experience with picture compression I got the best results
when I combined a simple pixel reduction system with a good data
compression system. As an example you can take an iff picture
and compress it with lha. It's prety well packed but you can get
more reduction if you create an initial compression format that
itself can be compressed. As an example to this I remember a
program that would process gif's in such a way that they would
compress better than they normaly would. Giving your initial
format some order will allow the 2nd phase to compress further than
it would if the initial phase creates "pure random" numbers.

I have very little time to discuss this but I hope I can
inspire you to experiment and dicover your own techniques
and maybe you'll be the one to discover a non lossy gfx
format to beat jpeg!

Cheers,

Paul

