Subject: Re: CODING/DECODING
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

Hi Berhan,

On 17-Dec-97, Berhan K wrote:

>what I had in mind is a picture-shrinker!
>the idea is this: need 2 cariables to store the picture data!
>1) Colour and 2)number of pixels

>so:
>1) for every picture do:
>2) for every pixel(starting 0-319, 0-255) read color
>3) if color(0) and color(1) are same index(0-255) then Colour=the colour
index
>of the pixel(s) and Number of  pixels=Number of pixels+1

>then save the data :
>it will look like this:

>3,2
>5,12
>129,4
>234,8
>for example, no?! SO:
>3,2 means - color index 3 will be plotted 2 pixels(startin 0-319, 0-255 -
left
>to rite)
>5,12 means color index 5 will be plotted 12 pixels (after the 3,2 plotting)
>129,4 means colour index 129 will contribute with 4 pixels
>234,8 as above and etc..

>and since it is a text(ascii data) it would be packed quite well..

>I want to consult the more experienced programmers on the list, is this a
>smart
>move or it just looks intressting? Or am I misstaken that it will decrease a
>file(picture)'s size?!

This is a good idea - but so good, that it has already been thought of long
ago...
You will find that all decent paint and image programs already compact their
pictures to the Amiga standard iff format. (this is what all these things
mean, iff, gif, jpeg, etc. are all different methods to compact pictures). For
example, the Amiga Lagoon picture that comes with Brilliance has a file size
of 490392.  But this picture is 896 x 860 x 256 colours, and so actually uses
770,560 bytes of memory!

Also, saving to a text file is not really very compact.  Each character in a
text file uses 1 byte, so the number 124 for example uses 3 bytes of disk
space, plus one extra byte for the carriage return character that is saved
with it to indicate the end of each entry.

Much more compact to save as binary, then each byte can represent a number
from 0-255.

Also, there is one other possible problem - imagine a picture with many colour
variations in it, for example a series of vertical stripes 1 pixel wide.  Now
the routine would wind up using 2 bytes to describe every one byte of the
picture!  So you could wind up with a saved file that was actually larger than
the original picture!  So you would also need to check for this.


-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
