> Also, there is one other possible problem - imagine a picture with
> many colour variations in it, for example a series of vertical stripes 1
> pixel wide.  Now the routine would wind up using 2 bytes to describe
> every one byte of the picture!  So you could wind up with a saved file
> that was actually larger than the original picture!  So you would also
> need to check for this.

   Very true, but you can get around this problem easily enough.  The
   first time I tackled my own compression/decompression systems
   I made a variant of the RLE system, although at the time I had no
   idea that's what it was actually called :)

   Anyway, by storing the data as WAR (Write As Read - just what I
   call it) along with pointers to the compressed sections then you
   can obtain decent compression and even if you encounter an image
   such as the one you described above, your "compressed" file will
   only be a few bytes larger than the actual image-size in ChipRAM.

   It works for samples as well and actually, that's why I developed it.
   I only managed around a 15% compression, but at the time I was
   quite happy..

  
      Take  care,   
      GARFIELD
