> kind of thing and it was the happiest time I ever spent programming :)

I bet it was. ;)

> From my experience with picture compression I got the best results
> when I combined a simple pixel reduction system with a good data
> compression system. As an example you can take an iff picture
> and compress it with lha. It's prety well packed but you can get
> more reduction if you create an initial compression format that
> itself can be compressed. As an example to this I remember a
> program that would process gif's in such a way that they would
> compress better than they normaly would. Giving your initial
> format some order will allow the 2nd phase to compress further than
> it would if the initial phase creates "pure random" numbers.

This is the kind of thing that the Burrow-Wheeler Transformation is doing=
=2E
And it efficiency is the better the bigger the data chunk is!
This BWT, as it is known, transforms input data in such way that it is in=

optimum order for the real compression algorythms. This leads to VERY goo=
d
compression rates even with less advanced compression alcorythm.

The WWW site is in the other mail I casted to this list. (I think. If not=

Mail to me!)

