To be honest, I have never done this.  I think you would need to set up a bank
to save the values to and then save this bank out as a binary file.  I'm sure
someone on the list knows how to do this better.

>> Also, there is one other possible problem - imagine a picture with
>> many colour
>> variations in it, for example a series of vertical stripes 1 pixel
>> wide.  Now
>> the routine would wind up using 2 bytes to describe every one byte of
>> the
>> picture!  So you could wind up with a saved file that was actually
>> larger than
>> the original picture!  So you would also need to check for this.

>that's a picture I'd like to see..I've been thinking about that and if
>You take a picture - ANY picture and examine it - You'll never see such
>a thing!

This was just an example, although I do have a couple of Commodore pics meant
for adjusting my flicker-fixer's video output that are very much like what I
described.
However, colour dithering is a very common technique widely used to show more
colours than are actually available on the screen.  This is done by
alternating pixels of two or more colours, for example alternating dark blue
and white will look like light blue on the screen.  Zoom in on different parts
of pictures in your painting program and you will find this frequently used,
especially in pictures that were originally made from photographs.  For a
quick example, zoom in on a MagicWorkbench Icon.

-- 
