On 19-Dec-97, C Dimitrakakis wrote:

> On Thu, 18 Dec 1997 07:57:50 +0100 Senguine/DiVE =

> <pt96bka%student.hk-r.se@uk.ac.essex.mailhost> wrote:

> > > Also, there is one other possible problem - imagine a picture with
> > > many colour
> > > variations in it, for example a series of vertical stripes 1 pixel
> > > wide.  Now
> > > the routine would wind up using 2 bytes to describe every one byte =
of
> > > the
> > > picture!  So you could wind up with a saved file that was actually
> > > larger than
> > > the original picture!  So you would also need to check for this.
> > =

> Sorrry, but this kind of picture would normally be compressed to =

> something smaller than say, 16 bytes, if the stripes are always the =

> same colour, if stripes are different colour will be compressed to say =

> 16-bytes*(width of picture) if the colour varies also with height, in a=
 =

> non-random way, then the same amount of compression is possible with =

> predictive encoding before compression, and well, if the colours always=
 =

> vary randomly, then you have a random-noise-picture, which is totally =

> useless anyway :) If there is only a 'bit' of noise, then lossy =

> compression techniques like jpeg can compress it to the same amount..

Well this conversation is for RLE coding and that would be twice the
original size. Of course the final coding would pack it.
Because the stripes would lead to height times of same number pairs
in the RLE coded file. like this

10,1
20,1
10,1
30,1
18,1
0,1last pixel in the line (So very narrow picture ;)
10,1
20,1
=2E..
=2E.
=2E

Well this is the case if using STRAIGHT RLE coding, but normally RLE
codes only, if there is more than two same colored pixels in a horizontal=

line.

