Once in my life, I was a cracker... So I have some experience with this stuff :)
It doesn't matter which kind of protection you use if it ends with an 'IF/ENDIF'
statement; it's easy to crack. It's some sort of tracing your code (in the exe)
and find the CMP, TST, BEQ, or BNE instructions. The good news are that compiled
code are HARDER to trace than pure asm :)

The best kind of protection I used (the easy one), was using machine code's EOR()
instruction, since if you run it once, it encrypts your data, and if used again,
it returns the original value. So, I used to encrypt some parts of the code itself
with the eor's from the ascii strings values (by hand), and when the program runs,
it eor's the same code parts with the strings values, but if they aren't the same,
the resulting code is corrupt, and it crashes itself :)

This technique is some tricky (because by rellocating data nature), it's very
useful. From asm, you can use some sort of LEA, MOVE with the PC arguement (to be
rellocatable too) to find your current position.

I hope this helps!!




@ENDNODE
