Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; CHARSET=US-ASCII


On Mon, 8 Dec 1997 17:53:57 GMT Mike Carter 
<57229007%mmu.ac.uk@uk.ac.essex.mailhost> wrote:

> > 
> > Hello all,
> > I am in need of a very fast horizontal line drawing routine.
> > This routine is ONLY required to draw horizontal line on
> > a bimap
> > of size 320*256 and a colour depth of 6 bitplanes.
> > 
> > Ideally the statement interface should be
> > drawline{x_pos1,y_pos1,x_pos2,y_pos2,colour}
> > I find the LINE command within blitz to be too slow....
> > 
> If the line is horizontal then surely the parameters would be...
> 
>  drawline{x_pos1,y_pos1,length,colour}
> 
> ...as you don't need to know the second y co-ordinate!
> Sorry I couldn't actually help with the problem :-)
> 
Hm, I think he means splitting the almost-horizontal line into many 
horizontal ones that can then use the horizontal-only line routine..
If you don't mind overwriting lines, then a good way to go is to:

Write an asm routine that splits the line then calls the horizontal 
routine. Ideally, all the loop should be in asm, and not just the 
draw_line procedure, since For/Next and While/Wend are very very very 
slow.
The horizontal draw routine itself should draw bytes on the bitplanes 
as this is much faster - this means that you might be getting an extra 
7 pixels on either side of each line segment, but if your lines are 
very :) horizontal and you don't mind overdrawing it shouldn't matter - 
otherwise (ie 45 degree lines) they would look rather thick and blocky 
:/
By the way, if you are drawing polygons as well, it might be a good 
idea to draw the polygons the same time as the lines, use the CPU to 
draw the lines and blitter to draw polygons or (the other way around if 
you want). Even better still, write your own, asynchronous 
blitter polygon drawing routine. :P)





Christos Dimitrakakis (aka Olethros)
Electronic Engineer,
Software Developer for the Amiga computer
University of Essex




@ENDNODE
