Hi,

>>   Well I once had this problem, The reason was because I had
>>   been programming in AMOS and was using some AMOS books.
>>   I tried to convert some examples from this to Blitz but
>>   I made the mistake of trying to alter as little code=20
>>   as possible instead of properly rewriting the code.
>>   And this problem with the Functions was confusing me a lot
>>   because AMOS didn`t have such stricked rules as blitz on this.
>
>Yes, this does mean that blitz is very strict but anything that
>forces you to program in a strict structured way is good. Spending
>a bit of time and thought on your code can save much more time
>and thought later on.

Yes, but that's not a great reason for having reduced functionality, =
because sometimes it might be needed.  I have a program that had two =
functions which called each other.  In this situation, rearranging them =
is not possible, so I had to write an extra function, which was a pain =
because I already had tons of functions.

>I think they should have removed Goto from Blitz which would
>have made it even better. So on my wish list for Blitz 3 would
>be to remove the goto command! :)

Why?  That just restricts things even more.  Until Blitz becomes a _lot_ =
more advanced, Goto/Gosub still come in handy.  I generally don't use =
them, but in one program I have a couple of statements that have about =
20 SHARED variables, because you can't have global variables.  Then =
there is the bug in statement/functions that under certain conditions, =
will trash one of the passed variables (I've fixed this bug though.)  =
You can't have static variables in procedures, so you have to make an =
extra SHARED variable for that.

It's things like these that need to be fixed, and until they are, =
Goto/Gosubs will still come in handy.

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid

BTW, did you get that AHI code I sent not long ago?





@ENDNODE
