Subject: Re: Functions Calls!!!
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

Hi Dave,

> Remove goto`s from Blitz that would be a crazy move!!
> I don`t use them much myself to avoid confusion and bad
> programming, But there have been times when I have found
> them useful. (once or twice)
> If you don`t want to use them don`t , but remove them from blitz
> and stop others using them would be limiting blitz and would be
> pointless.

I can understand you but I see quite a lot of source code that
people send to me and they ask me to help them fix a few bugs.
I take one look at the code and it's full of goto's and I can't
understand the program logic they're trying to use. This is an
example of how Goto is wasting time and making it hard to track
down bugs. Sometimes I would reply to them saying I couldn't figure
out what the hell was going on but other times I would edit the
code to work without gotos and it would be much times easier to
follow and probably 3 times smaller. If only people were forced
to learn how to do things properly they would get better results.

I spent 10 years learning to programm by myself and I thought I
was really good at it. Then I went to college to learn C and
structured programming. Now I know about all the things I used
to do wrong and the last 5 years of my programming life have been
the most productive ever.

If all those BASIC languages I learnt when I started programming
didn't have the goto command I would probably would have learnt
many of those structured programming skills earlier.

The only argument for the use of goto is that maybe in some rare
cases it could be the fastest option. Speed can somtimes be more
important than easy to follow code and as long as speed is the
most important thing then you should use any technique you want.
If you do use bad structure then you've only got yourself to
blame when you waste a whole day tracking down bugs. You have
to compare the advantages over the disadvantages, if you use good
structure your code will often be faster, smaller and much easier
to maintain and upgrade.
Cheers,

Paul

-- 
