X-Mailer: YAM 1.3.4 - Amiga Mailer by Marcel Beck
Subject: Re: Functions Calls!!!
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

>On 04-Jan-80, Julian Kinraid wrote:
>> Hi,

>> >be to remove the goto command! :)

>> Why?  That just restricts things even more.  Until Blitz becomes a _lot_
>more
>> advanced, Goto/Gosub still come in handy.  I generally don't use them, but
>in
>> one program I have a couple of statements that have about 20 SHARED
>variables,
>> because you can't have global variables.  Then there is the bug in
>> statement/functions that under certain conditions, will trash one of the
>> passed variables (I've fixed this bug though.)  You can't have static
>> variables in procedures, so you have to make an extra SHARED varia
>> ble for that.

>> It's things like these that need to be fixed, and until they are,
>Goto/Gosubs
>> will still come in handy.

I think by "static" variables he means having local variables within your
function that are preserved until the next time the function is called.  This
would
be much better, since the only way to do this now is to set up a program
variable
outside the function, and have it "shared" too.

And the "global" variables doesn't mean that all your variables must be global
- only the ones you want to set up that way.

You could still have "shared" variables, just like now - only you wouldn't
have to do this for the ones that are needed by ALL your functions.

And normal program variables that are ignored by the functions.

These would be excellent additions, and would save a lot of confusion.

As far as removing the GoTo and GoSub commands - WHY?  I have used them myself
without problems to avoid situations like above, with 20 shared variables in a
function, and some of them really specific to that function only.

If every command that could be mis-used was removed from Blitz, there wouldn't
be much left would there?

I would rather see the manual written a little better to explain the use and
mis-use of the commands.  Then beginners wouldn't overuse these so much if it
was explained how to do it properly.

Bye for now, and Season's Greetings to all.
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
