Subject: Re: Functions Calls!!!
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

Hi C,

> > I'd be happy to see an example where a Goto is needed.

> Here's a funny one: A jumptable.
> A bit like a case statement I guess, but not quite the same
> since it can change dynamically.
> jtable.l(32)
>
> getreg d0,jtable(x)
> TokeJsr Goto

Well this is almost like going into Asm for speed but using
the Basic command to make a point ;) If you wanted to do this sort
of thing then pure Asm would be better. I'm not so good with Asm
but couldn't you do somthing like this:

GetReg a0,jtable(x)
BRA a0

or

GetReg a0,jtable(x)
Move.l a0,PC

Or whatever the correct Assembler syntax is :) The point is, the
only time you should consider getting away from proper structure
is if you need the speed or you want to do things in a low level
way eg, Asm code. We can see from the above example that straying
from proper structure makes the code almost unreadable and you're
better of doing what you want to do in proper Asm. I know we
could say that we need the speed all of time but doing things in
an unstructured way with a high level language is missing the
point. An argument was made that Beginers shouldn't be forced to
use a strict programming language but the only example for a good
use of goto is when you want to do advanced coding. The existance
of the command is only making life harder for beginers.

Cheers,

Paul

