Hi everyone,

On 29-Dec-97, Garfield Benjamin wrote:
>> Hmm, seems to be hardcoded to read the 29th byte. I'm sure that'll
>> fail eventually unless the CMAP is always in the same location.
>> Searching for "CMAP" and reading from there is probably safer.

>   Yes... in all my tests the 29th-byte of a IFF palette, brush or picture
>   file contained the number of bitplanes, so it's *probably* reliable...
>   I'm not guaranteeing anything as it has been a while since I was into
>   decoding these IFF-structures...

No, Paul is right - some programs add an "ANNO" chunk to the iff file.
For example Brilliance adds a "Written by Brilliance BLAH BLAH BLAH", and this
would appear at the location you are checking.  So instead of getting the
bitplanes, you would always get the value of the letter "t" or whatever is
there.

AdPro also adds an "ANNO" chunk, and there are probably others.

BTW, if you load one of these pics into DPaint and re-save it, these "ANNO"
chunks are removed  (and DPaint doesn't add one)

PPaint doesn't add one either, but won't remove any that exist in the original
pic.

  
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
