Hey :]

>You can use Inkey$, EventCode, or KeyCode to read the keypresses.
>Try the small test code below.  You will find that Inkey$ responds
>to all character keys (Alt A gives a different value than just A),
>EventCode ignores everything but the key (Alt A, shift A, Ctrl A
>all give the same value), and KeyCode responds to all except the
>shift key.

How about using RawKey along with Qualifier after detecting a keypress?

Use RawKey to get the value of the key and then check the Qualifier.
Qualifier returns a value corresponding to which shift, control, alt, amiga
keys were held down and also if the Caps Lock is currently on. 

I think it's probably better to do it using Event and then these functions
rather than Inkey$ as Inkey$ can, I think, sometimes behave strangely and may
not be totaly system friendly...

Andrew
