Message-ID: <34AA170C.800C3C89@pavilion.co.uk>
Date: Wed, 31 Dec 1997 09:57:32 +0000
From: Liz Tucker <tucks@pavilion.co.uk>
Organization: Desktop Corruption
X-Mailer: Mozilla 4.01 [en] (Win95; I)
MIME-Version: 1.0
To: Blitz-list <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Subject: Re: IncXXX
X-Priority: 3 (Normal)
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit


Peter Thor wrote:
> 
> I would like to take advantage of the inclib library in order to
> include different shapes, bitmaps etc, but it seems i need a special
> program in order to decode each object into its proper binary data...
> 
> The problem is i havent got this program and dont know where to get it
> either.. anyone of u  guys know? or maybe a better way of including
> various objects?

Hi Peter,

I think you are making this more complicated than it really is.

All you need to do is set up a label at the end of you code, after an
End command so that it can never be executed, and INCBIN the data at
that label. Then in your code you use the DecodeXXXXX commands to read
the data from that memory location in the same way that the various
LoadXXXX commands read in the data from the disk.

eg...

< your program is here >
End

mylabel
INCBIN "mypic.iff"

------------------------------------

That is the bottom of you program. Now somewhere near the top you will
have your Loading routine. Here you will have to following...

MyLoadingRoutine

< Load various things from disk >

DecodeILBM mybitmap,?mylabel     ; earlier you program would have   
                                 ; defined the bitmap ready 
< Finish any more loading >      ; for use.

Continue with the program here

-------------------------------------

All of the various Decode commands work in the same way and will work on
the Shape, iff, MOD or what ever it is as if you were loading it from
disk.

Note however that during development the incbin stuff will be loaded
from disk as it is only included in the file when as .exe is created.

Hope this has made it a bit clearer for you.

Happy New Year. :)
-- 
See you,

Liz.                     tucks@pavilion.co.uk
  
