 Hello,

Well I had a look at the source code for the Derby  game  that
you  sent  to  the  list,  and  I  have  a  few  comments  and
suggestions on how to improve it. First I whould like  to  say
that  this  code is one of the codes I tend to call the "After
two weeks you dont know what does what" code. This is  because
of all the messed up jumpings and comments.

First I think that all the development comments (The ones  you
put  at the top of the source) should be put in a text file of
it's own. This is to clean up the code.

Secondly I whould like to suggest that you stoped using goto's
and  gosub's.  They  will  only  mess  up  the code. Try using
Statements and Functions, it can be done, and it will make the
code  much  smarter  and  easyer  to  read threw as an outside
person.

You should also try to put all the comments  in  one  straight
line.  Lets  say  all  commets  are written in column 70. This
whould make it even easyer to read.

When using Statement's and Function's you tend to get a  quite
nice  bunch  of  Shared  variabels,  and  they can mess up the
statements. So try and make they  "fake  globals"  by  putting
them  in  a macro which you then call from your statements and
functions. Something like this.

Macro Globals                 ; Create global variabels
  SHARED CarSpeed             ; Stores the cars speed
  SHARED CarDamage            ; Stores the cars damage
  SHARED Score                ; Stores player score
  SHARED CarXPos              ; Horizontal position of the car
  SHARED CarYPos              ; Vertical position of the car
End Macro                     ; End of global variabels

Statement CheckCollision{}    ; Collision checking routine
 !Globals                     ; Get the global variabels
      ;
 <other source>               ; Collision checking stuff
      ;
End Statemant                 ; End of Collision checking

Another thing to keep the code even more readebal and smart is
to  keep  all  the Statements and Functions in a seperat file,
which you then include. I know many people on this  list  will
say  "No  that  only stupide", but if you use it the right way
then it will pay of, since your "main" code (The one with  the
repeat - until) will be much shorter and readebal.

We at Vivid Imagination has spent alot of  time  to  keep  our
source codes very easy to read and get into, since we are more
then noe person that code at the same  project,  and  we  dont
want  to  wast 2hours just so that we understand the code that
someone has written.

By using the things I've just told you, we have been  abel  to
avoid  this  kind  of  stuff.  And  I can tell you that as the
founder - organiser and one of the coders in Vivid Imagination
you  need  to  have  somekind  of smart system to make it work
within a group that has many people involved.

Well thats is, there are of course more you can do,  but  this
is the big parts that can be used. Hope this helps. And ohyeah
the collision detecting can be a b*tch like you've  discoverd,
not  only  with  the  walls, but also with other cars, so that
they dont "crawl" up on  eachother.  When  I  was  a  part  of
another  team  we made a 4 player car game, and had these kind
of problems, but we managed  to  solve  them.  And  using  256
colors  shouldn't  have  to slow you down, we used it and good
excellent speed outof the game. And we also used a 2*2  screen
mode  (4 screens total). If you have any questions then please
feel free to mail me directly.

  Good ByE! - And a Happy New Year!

-- =

