On 16-Dec-97, Alvaro Thompson wrote:
AT>Sorry if I mailed this LONG mail to the list (my apologies if anyone
AT>thinks this is unnecessary), but I just wondered what everyone thinks
AT>about the current Coding languages situation, and what did everyone
AT>think of this guy's attitude???

Right, a couple of facts first:

Excel, like all Microsoft applications, is written in Visual C++.

VB is not a good language to learn programming in. It teaches MANY bad
habits. /real/ programmers wouldn't touch it with a barge pole :)


My advice, as someone who recently did a college course and now works as
a programmer, is to go somewhere that teaches C and C++. C should be the
foundation of you real-world programming knowledge as that is what
everything is based on. Once you know C, VB is (too) simple. Once you
know C++, Java is just a short hop.

A course should also do at least something on the internet. The web is
vitalling important in all companies involved in the computer industry
and to ignore it is plain stupid.

Java and JavaScript can be easily self-taught if you have a good book and
knowledge of C++. Much can also be found about these on the internet.
Also, forget about VBScript. Nobody uses it because JavaScript is much
better.

Learning some basic SQL could also be helpful as you will find it crops
up all over the place.

This is just my experience of college and work. I hope it is useful.

Bye,
Alex

-- 
+-- Alex Wingrove / awingrove@thenet.co.uk --+

