Alvaro Thompson walked into a door and muttered something about "Microsoft? Ewwwwwww" 
> I was rather, shall I say, "scared" above all. I don't mean by the guy (well,
> sort of, he was a bit of an asshole), but rather by his attitude.
Yeah, these are the guys that think they know everything, but most
often don't.  Something to do with being in a position of power, or
something.

 This guy
> seemed to think that Microsoft products are the way to the future, and that
> their products are really great!!! I was thinking to myself at that moment
> "Mmmmmm......... My ass". We then went onto the subject of programming, and I
> told him that I did a fair bit of programming at home, as a hobby, and also
> HTML and crap. He then told me that in the BTEC course, we would be learning
> Visual Basic! I then sort of dropped a sarcastic comment like "Mmmm.........
> Visual Basic.... GRRRRRRRREAT". I told him that what I really wanted to learn
> was more Java, Javascript, and C stuff, and then he came out with this speech
> "Yes, we used to teach all these things, Java, Javascript, C, Pascal, all of
> that! but the 'in' thing now is Visual Basic, all the great applications like
> MS-Excell are written in it". This was most distressing. GREAT APPLICATION???

Sounds like the dept head at my uni, he's a fully paid up member of
the "I Love Bill Gates Society", but at least he realises that C is
far better than VB!

> Sorry if I mailed this LONG mail to the list (my apologies if anyone thinks
> this is unnecessary), but I just wondered what everyone thinks about the
> current Coding languages situation, and what did everyone think of this guy's
> attitude???
>
You're right about the "in" language thing, you'd be taking a big
chance learning it just because it's "in", trends change so quickly.
(just think how quickly the Buzz Lightyear toys have been forgotten =)

Besides, if you learn VB, you'll only have Windows programming
experiences (and I know they won't be good ones either!) but if you
learn C or C++ you will be able to program for any computer with a C
compiler - which I think narrows it down to roughly all of them :)
If your serious about progamming then I would advise learning C or
C++.  If you have the chance then learn the Web related stuff as well
- a friend of the family funded his way through Uni a few years ago by
writing web pages, one company paid him 6K for 10 pages of HTML!!!
These people are mad, so you might as well make some money off them
when you can :)



