X-Mailer: YAM 1.3.5 [020] - Amiga Mailer by Marcel Beck
Organization: Team Mango
Subject: MUD Server
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain


Hi Blitzers!

We are in need of help. As you may know, I have already sent a few E-Mails
about this. Me and gareth tried to understand the TCP code which Paul Burkey
did, but we only managed to make it so that it gets input from one of the
nodes, but we did't manage to get it to that it only sent messages to a
certain node.

I would appreciate if someone out there would take part in the production of
this MUD, by writing all the TCP Protocols for it. It doesn't have to be in
Blitz, as long as the person can make the program write messages to a certain
dstination, eg RAM:, then the two programs can communicate from there. This is
what we'd like:

The whole point of this, is for our MUD server, which is called Time Scope. As
you may know, MUD Servers are pretty advanced, but we just need a few simple
intructions, on how to do certain things:

We need to login Users into "nodes" just like Paul Burkey's TCP Example, which
uses Nodes 1-4.

Is there any way in which you could help us, by modifying the code a bit? Here
is what we propose:

* The TimeScope game server writes a file to RAM:
   On the first line of the file is the node to which the message is to be
   sent. On the second line is the actual message

* The TCP shite reads in this file, sending the message to the given node.

* The TCP shite finds out if any new messages have been sent, and if so,
writes a new file
   to RAM: which contains the node # on the first line and the message on the
second.

* The TimeScope server receives this new file.

* When a new player logs in, a new file is written to RAM: containing the node
# used, and a      message to say that this node has joined ($$Join in this
case.)

We'd be really greatfull if you could spare some of your time to do this.....
we are in desperate help for this. We were hoping to have the server up and
running soon, a sort of demo version. We have found someone who has a 24hr
Internet Connection, and is willing to put it on-line. There's a bit of
advertising atm, by Telnetting timescope.tibb.at:4000. Also, a web site will
follow (www.timescope.tibb.at).

If you do help us, the minimum we could do is give you "God" status in the
MUD, which will allow you to also edit the MUD, and become part of the whole
project!

We need your HELP NOW!!!!


-- 

=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
| Alvaro Thompson - http://homepages.enterprise.net/alvaro/
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
| A1200T, '030, 10MB, 1.74Gb, 4x IDE, M1438S, BJC-4200, Dynalink 33.6K
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

"Hey Mr. Where you headed? Are you in a hurry?" - Hitchin' a Ride, Greenday



@ENDNODE
