From: Andreas =?iso-8859-1?Q?H=E5kansson?= <andy@bjuv.mail.telia.com>
To: blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie
Date: Sun, 07 Dec 1997 20:25:46 +0100
Message-ID: <yam7280.2309.140897992@m1.418.telia.com>
In-Reply-To: <yam7280.1525.3952936@mail.geocities.com>
X-Mailer: YAM 1.3.4 [020] - Amiga Mailer by Marcel Beck
Subject: MUI Custom Classes - Once and for all
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable


Well  since it doesn't seem how many times
I  tell  the  people  on  the list to send
questions  like  this, to   us   at  Vivid
Imagination, and  not to the blitz mailing
list, I might aswell awnser this  question
here (And thisis not to be rude, but since
the people on the list dont know how to do
the MUI  stuff yet. I  know, I  get  mails
everyday asking how to do stuff.).

Well what  you  basicly  have  to do is to
convert  the   custom class .h  file, into
a blitz  basic file, which you then whould
include into your own program.

Lets assume we want to use a  custom class
thats called TestClass.mcc, then the first
thing we whould have  to do is  to convert
the .h file  that comes  with  the  custom
class. In this case the file is called
NewClass_mcc.h.

Now what we want  to do is to take all the
tags thats beeing defigned and change them
into blitz  basic  constants. Some  of the
tags may have a 10 digit long value to the =

right if  itself, that  may look like this
0x90a40001, the  part we  need  from  this
10  digits  is the  last 8,  so  we whould
only use  90a4001 (the stuff after the x).

Now that you  know this I can make a short
example. Here is a  example  what  a C tag
whould be in blitz basic.

 IN C

   #define MUIA_ThisIsATest 0x901a238d

 IN BLITZ

   #MUIA_ThisIsATest=3D901a238d

Now after you have converted all the  tags
you  should   save  your  file,  and  then
include it  into  your blitz program using
the INCLUDE command.

Then when you want to use the custom class
in  question (In  this case NewClass.mcc),
you whould have to do the following.

  MUIAddTags <num>,<the tags you want>
  MUINewObject <num>,"NewClass.mcc",0

This should work. I havn't tried it myself
but thats the way to get the new tags that
the customclass uses. If  you  think  that
there are many tags  to  adapt, then  just
image what  a job we had  to  do, when  we
converted all the  standard  MUI tags into
blitz basic constants.

Please send  us  at  Vivid Imagiantion the
custom classes files that you have adapted
so we can include  it  in  an archive with
the lib, so that  everyone  whouldn't have
to do the same work over  and over  again,
when  it's  already been done. All we want
is the file with the  tags in, and not the
whole custom class. Please  send  a  short
example on how to use the class aswell. We
reserve  us  the  right  to  tidy  up  the
example source, and  the  inlude file. Not
chnage anything, just tidy up the code, so
it  will  be  easy  to read and understand
(if it's not  already  that way ofcourse).
You will  get  full  credit for your work.
Keep  in mind  that  we  wont  include  to
include  files of  the same  custom class,
we will use  the first/best one. Same goes
for the examples for the class.

 ByE


-- =

=2E-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D=
-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-=3D-.
