Reply-To: awingrove@thenet.co.uk
To: Blitz List <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Date: Mon, 15 Dec 1997 22:31:34 -0000
Message-ID: <yam7288.1742.30595472@smtp.thenet.co.uk>
In-Reply-To: <yam7288.1947.2016814208@mail.enterprise.net>
X-Mailer: YAM 1.3.4 [040] - Amiga Mailer by Marcel Beck
Subject: Re: Object objects objects!
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

On 15-Dec-97, Alvaro Thompson wrote:
AT>What's the difference between an "Object-orientated" language, and an
AT>"Object-Based" language? For what I know... Java (and javascript) are
AT>object based, and MUI, for example, if Object-Orientated. What's the
AT>different someone?

Object-Oriented means you make use of objects in a procedural way. In
other words, MUI is made up of objects, but you can use them in a
procedural language like Blitz. C++ is like this too.

Java, on the other hand, is made of objects through-and-through.
Everything in Java is an object so you are always writing in an
Object-oriented environment. Therefore it's Object-based. C++ can also be
like this, but writing everything as an object in C++ is a real pain (
MFC's anyone? :)

As for which is better, I prefer object-based. However, no-one has
written the perfect language for it yet. Java is fiddly and C++ too
complicated and time consuming. Delphi is well-arranged, but based on
pascal (ugh!). How about Object-Based Blitz?

I hope that helps a bit.

Bye,
Alex

-- 
+-- Alex Wingrove / awingrove@thenet.co.uk --+

[      www.thenet.co.uk/~awingrove/blitz/       ]
[ Blitz Program Collection  and  Blitz List FAQ ]



