	by mserv1a.u-net.net with smtp (Exim 1.73 #4)
	id 0xj7iI-0003nS-00; Fri, 19 Dec 1997 19:04:07 +0000
Received: (qmail 21522 invoked by alias); 19 Dec 1997 19:03:24 -0000
Mailing-List: contact blitz-list-help@netsoc.ucd.ie; run by ezmlm
Delivered-To: mailing list blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie
Received: (qmail 21517 invoked from network); 19 Dec 1997 19:03:23 -0000
Received: from seralph10.essex.ac.uk (155.245.240.160)
  by orca.ucd.ie with SMTP; 19 Dec 1997 19:03:23 -0000
Received: from fpgapc16.essex.ac.uk by seralph10.essex.ac.uk; (5.65v3.2/1.1.8.2/14Feb95-1154AM)
	id AA01892; Fri, 19 Dec 1997 19:03:16 GMT
From: C Dimitrakakis <cdimita@essex.ac.uk>
To: BlitzList <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Subject: On Compression
Message-Id: <SIMEON.9712191943.F@fpgapc16.essex.ac.uk>
Date: Fri, 19 Dec 1997 19:03:43 +0000 (GMT)
Priority: NORMAL
X-Mailer: Simeon for Win32 Version 4.1.2 Build (32)
X-Authentication: IMSP
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; CHARSET=US-ASCII

Guys(and gals), its OK having loads of fun developing your own 
compression formats, but I urge you to PLEASE take a look at source 
coding text books to understand the basic compression theory first - 
this will also introduce you to the best general compression techniques 
available (the original and the best) - then you can read a bit on 
compression techniques for specific sources. These invariantly start 
with altering the representation of the source, do some kind of 
compression themselves, and then use some of the general (original and 
best) compression techniques to actually compress the source.

The best places to look for image/sound compression is the IEEE 
journals (ie the IEEE Image Processing Journal)...

BTW, if you want non-lossy compression, then in most cases the easiest 
thing to do is to use predictive encoding. This looks at the source, 
which is say, an 8-bit sample and compresses it by trying to predict 
the next sample value using n previous values. It compares the 
prediction with the actual value, and gets e(i)=Spredict(i)-Sreal(i)
- and what it stores is the actual error values.
Depending on your prediction algorithm, these errors are quite small, 
and usually follow some kind of pattern that is easy for say, lha to 
compress to a tiny amount.

When you decompress, first you use the simple decompression technique 
to get all the error values e(), then you recreate the source by using 
the inverse prediction function..

Using simple linear prediction, you can compress speech samples to 
about a quarter of their original size.



Christos Dimitrakakis (aka Olethros)
Electronic Engineer,
Software Developer for the Amiga computer
University of Essex
http://esewww.essex.ac.uk/~cdimita



@ENDNODE
