	id 0xfrmp-0005S5-00; Wed, 10 Dec 1997 19:27:11 +0000
Received: (qmail 10546 invoked by alias); 10 Dec 1997 19:26:35 -0000
Mailing-List: contact blitz-list-help@netsoc.ucd.ie; run by ezmlm
Delivered-To: mailing list blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie
Received: (qmail 10541 invoked from network); 10 Dec 1997 19:26:34 -0000
Received: from seralph10.essex.ac.uk (155.245.240.160)
  by orca.ucd.ie with SMTP; 10 Dec 1997 19:26:34 -0000
Received: from fpgapc14.essex.ac.uk by seralph10.essex.ac.uk; (5.65v3.2/1.1.8.2/14Feb95-1154AM)
	id AA17158; Wed, 10 Dec 1997 19:26:24 GMT
From: C Dimitrakakis <cdimita@essex.ac.uk>
To: BlitzList <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Subject: On signed numbers
Message-Id: <SIMEON.9712101920.B@fpgapc14.essex.ac.uk>
Date: Wed, 10 Dec 1997 19:26:20 +0000 (GMT)
Priority: NORMAL
X-Mailer: Simeon for Win32 Version 4.1.2 Build (32)
X-Authentication: IMSP
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; CHARSET=US-ASCII

Internally, the 68k treats signed and unsigned numbers the same when 
doing adding or subtracting operations.
This is because signed binary numbers are represented by a two's 
complement representation (which you'd have to read about in case you 
don't know what it is), and the add/sub operators work the same on both 
nornal and two's complement binary numbers.
Shifting, multiplying and dividing operators have to work differently 
on signed/unsigned numbers.

That's why you get Logic shift and Arithmetic shift.
Use logic shift for unsigned numbers and arithmetic shift for signed.

Anyway, for most purposes, turning off overflow checking in Blitz will 
make it not mess around with signed/unsigned numbers, but...

the 68k has two kinds of multiply and divide instructions, one for 
signed numbers and one for unsigned. Blitz seems to be calling a 
special routine that somehow, through some strange tricks, always uses 
the Unsigned version of the instructions.. I think that you might 
experience problems with that if you try and multiply something with a 
number that is greater than the maximum SIGNED value allowed (ie, 127 
for a byte operation).

Hope gives some further insight.


Christos Dimitrakakis (aka Olethros)
Electronic Engineer,
Software Developer for the Amiga computer
University of Essex




