> By tripple buffering he probably means using a 3rd buffer that only 
> stores the background. This way you can use Qblit instead of bblit
> (you have to use the 2nd form of the Unqueue command). This is
> halfway between normal Qblit and bblit in speed.. - of course if you
> use custom blitting routines it can be even faster.

   Hmmm... "real" triple-buffering is actually just like double-buffering,
   only you are creating and cycling between three bitmaps.

   To understand why...

   Standard Double-buffering process:

1.   Display "Visible" Bitmap
2.   Update "Hidden" Bitmap
3.   Hold program while synchronizing with raster
4.   Swap "Visible" and "Hidden"   

   Triple buffering attempts to eliminate the bottleneck caused by the
   third step.

   By setting an interrupt to swap your bitmap into view, the 
   Triple Buffering process becomes something like this:

1.  Display "Visible" Bitmap
2.  Update "Hidden1" Bitmap
3.  Cycle "Hidden1" to "Visible", "Hidden2" to "Hidden1" and "Visible"
     to "Hidden2" -- just switching pointers so it's faster than it looks!
4.  Start Updating "Hidden2" Bitmap
  
   Not explaining it very well, but by cycling through 3 bitmaps, you
   waste memory, but you can gain max speed as just sitting around
   waiting for the raster every frame is a huge bottleneck!!


      Take  care,   
      GARFIELD
