 Sun, 07 Dec 1997 20:28:11 -0500
Message-ID: <B0000153519@mailhost.sosbbs.com>
From: "Garfield Benjamin" <gbenjam@sosbbs.com>
To: "BLITZ MAILING LIST" <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Subject: Re: Screen Double Buffering ??
Date: Sun, 7 Dec 1997 20:34:41 -0500
X-MSMail-Priority: Normal
X-Priority: 3
X-Mailer: Microsoft Internet Mail 4.70.1155
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

[regarding triple-buffering...]
> How is it different to double-buffering - why can't you just change
> pointers for double-buffering? If you didn't sync up to the VBL your
> triple-buffering would run a varible frame rate wouldn't it?

   As you know, in double-buffering, you only have two bitmaps, one
   is being displayed while the other is being "rendered".

   You MUST wait for the raster to synchronize your bitmap-swapping 
   or you'll end up with a flickery mess of a display. Likewise, you
   MUST wait for the raster and have swapped your bitmaps before
   you can update the "hidden" bitmap for the next frame or you'll end
   up with a flickery mess of a display.

   With triple buffering, you'd actually have something like this (please
   forgive any errors in BLITZ commands as I am writing  this on my
   IBMclone)...

   Visible.b=0
   Hidden.b=1
  
   ClrInt 5
   SetInt 5
      Display Bitmap 0,Visible.b,0,0
   End SetInt

   Repeat
      Use Bitmap Hidden
      CLEAR_ALL_YOUR_BOBS
      UPDATE_YOUR_BOB-OBJECTS
      DRAW_YOUR_BOBS
      Visible=QWrap(Visible+1,0,3)
      Hidden=QWrap(Hidden+1,0,3)
   Until Joyb(0)

   Now, our program can run at max speed focusing on processing
   code and updating gfx.  We only switch bitmap pointers after we
   have completely "rendered" a new bitmap, so the interrupt-switch
   will never display a bitmap which is in the process of "rendering",
   and that is what happens if we try the above with only two bitmaps.

   Bear in mind that this is really only useful for programs which are
   written in highly optimized code.  Basically, the faster your updating
   and drawing everything the more you will gain by moving to a
   triple-buffering method.

   This is why in IBMclone games, triple-buffering is a "common" 
   technique as 100MHz+ CPU-speeds can do a LOT of processing
   and drawing in the time we'd be wasting to synch with the raster!!!!

   If you have a fast Amiga, you should see some decent speed
   increases as well, on a 14MHz machine with fast RAM, you might
   get another bob or two at 50/60fps.


      Take  care,   
      GARFIELD
      _________________________
      Current projects...
