On 09-Dec-97, Anton Reinauer wrote:
>On 08-Dec-97, Garfield Benjamin wrote:
>>[regarding triple-buffering...]
>  =

>>   Now, our program can run at max speed focusing on processing
>>   code and updating gfx.  We only switch bitmap pointers after we
>>   have completely "rendered" a new bitmap, so the interrupt-switch
>>   will never display a bitmap which is in the process of "rendering",
>>   and that is what happens if we try the above with only two bitmaps.

>   Ah-hah - I see what you mean- your program isn't waiting around in
>the vertical blank period, doing nothing :-)   How do you make sure your=

>program runs at a smooth frame rate? Because if there wasn't much
>happening onscreen and it didn't have much do to, it could render two
>frames in one VBL, and you'd skip a frame.   =


Well that Triple buffering is only usefull, if you are doing game that is=

NOT synced to VBI. This because action type games can NOT run in differen=
t
speed, it have to be smooth to be playable. So that's why it have to rend=
er
the screen in one VBI and thou the extrabuffer is useless.
In action game you could use 2.5 buffering thou. :)
I mean keep your background in extra buffer and use it as background
source in your blittings.


