On 03-Dec-97, Wright J.A wrote:
>    =


>>Well the frontier most likely is using just the blitter. BUT it
>will
>>calculate new lines while the blitting is done. and after the
>blit is
>>finished an interrupt handler then writes next blit to the
>blitter.
>>With this way you can draw a whole lot more polygons than using
>normal
>>blitting commands from blitz. Disavantage is that you have to
>write your
>>own blitting routines... And that can be pain in the a**!

>      So when using the Polyf command to get the blitter to draw
>polygons, it actually stops program execution (cpu), until blitter is
>finished???? I thought part of the point of the blitter is that it can
>run in parrallel with the cpu!! or is this not the case with Blitz?

well when the polyf are drawed blitter first draws the required lines
and then fills it. Now it have the polygon filled but it is only in one
bitplane. So it then copy the bitplane to every required bitplane in the
bitmap (or if the color requires zeros in the bitplane it clears it).
When the last blit is started the code execution will continue.

>     How come in Frontier on a fast cpu, it runs soooo much smoother...
>this is why i wondered if the polygons where being drawn with the CPU,
>as i `ve noticed that when using the blitter to draw things, even on a
>much faster cpu there is very little speed increase, because the blitter=

>still goes at the same speed.

but when you got faster CPU it calculates the rotations and projections
much faster so the blitter have job all the time. In slower CPUs the
blitter is not working all the time.

>>I'm writing such code in asm and I think it could be translated
>as series
>>of statements or functions... but the statement handling in the
>midle is
>>quite slow so it would be better way of doing it in big asm
>statement.
>>So you would need a big punch of asm coding skill to do that.

>      Heh... i am learning asm, and i would say that i can code in it
>now... i`ve written my own cpu bitmap clearing routine, and it`s quite
>nice  8)  I hate using statements....   subroutines are faster :)
>whats the quickest way to transfer a blitz variable to a cpu register??
>GetReg ? OR calling a statement, and passing the variables as parametrs,=

>which then are put automatically into the data registers??  i assume
>that GetReg is faster, but i am unsure. =


I think its quite even. Of course it also depends what you are doing how
many parameters and so on.

But if you are looking really fast use asm declarations and write to thes=
e.

example:

poke.l ?here,a.l
poke.l ?here+4,b.l
poke.l ?here+8,c.l
poke.l ?here+12,d.l

leahere,a0; Put the address here to A0
move.l(a0)+,d0; Take the values from here
move.l(a0)+,d1
move.l(a0)+,d2
move.l(a0)+,d3

move.ld0,-(a0); And put them back in reverse order
move.ld1,-(a0)
move.ld2,-(a0)
move.ld3,-(a0)

end

here: dc.l 0,0,0,0

so after executing this the variables a, b, c and d are in reverse order
ie. d, c, b and a in the label here.


>>OH and almost forget to say. Using CPU to clear the bitmap
>witch was >just
>>shown while the blitter is still drawing to the other could
>speed things up
>>framatically.
>how do i get it to use my routine, WHILE blitting???

You should write your own blitting routines... the interrupt code is quit=
e
easy to do using the setint command.

>>>keep on Blitzing........ and in 3D application some Asm
>wouldn't hurt either.   =

>I really like the way you can just shove Asm in Blitz :)

Yep. its nice.

BTW anybody knowing how the binary including is working??
Fast?
Reliable?
Easy to use?
This because I could take some move16 to my C2P code too!!
And in some cases the FPU commands could be really big help!!

