Hi,

>>      Heh... i am learning asm, and i would say that i can code in it
>>now... i`ve written my own cpu bitmap clearing routine, and it`s quite
>>nice  8)  I hate using statements....   subroutines are faster :)
>>whats the quickest way to transfer a blitz variable to a cpu =
register??
>>GetReg ? OR calling a statement, and passing the variables as =
parametrs,
>>which then are put automatically into the data registers??  i assume
>>that GetReg is faster, but i am unsure.=20

> I think its quite even. Of course it also depends what you are doing =
how
> many parameters and so on.

I would avoid GetReg if possible.  Each time you call it, it pushes lots =
of registers onto the stack, fetches the variable, then pulls the =
registers back off the stack.

Using statements/functions are faster, and fastest of all is to write =
them in a lib, as this avoids some of the code that statements/functions =
use.

> BTW anybody knowing how the binary including is working??
> Fast?
> Reliable?
> Easy to use?

I haven't used it myself, but I would assume you just -

bin:  INCBIN "data/code.bin"

and just jump to bin: to execute that code.

> This because I could take some move16 to my C2P code too!!
> And in some cases the FPU commands could be really big help!!

If you're interested I've written a program that lets you type in an =
instruction, eg. mulu.l d0,d1:d2, and it will give you the data for that =
command back, eg. DC.w $47c5.   It uses PhxAss, so any command that =
PhxAss supports can be used, except using labels.  I have an idea on how =
to use labels, but I don't know whether it's worthwile adding it.  It =
would let you use commands like -
jmp ([tabel,pc],d0.w*4)

I could develop it further, but I don't know if I have time or whether =
it's worth it, but you can have it anyway :)

Ciao,
Julian Kinraid



@ENDNODE
