X-MimeOle: Produced By Microsoft MimeOLE Engine V4.71.1008.3

Hi Andre,

>Could someone of you explain, you I can set the font of titlebars of =
windows
>and screens? Look at the following part of my source (not executable):

>  scrtag.taglist\a\a=3D#LikeWorkbench,False
>  scrtag.taglist\b\a=3D#Width,\wi
>  ...  <setting tags>
>  scrtag.taglist\l\a=3D#SysFont,0

I assume that these constants are the same as #WA_Width or #WA_...?

>  ...
>  Use IntuiFont 0
> scree.l=3DOpenScreenTagList_(False,&scrtag\a\a)
>  ScreenToFront_(&scree)
>  FindScreen 0,Scr
>  Use Screen 0

The problem is that OpenScreenTagList() is an OS command, and it will =
probably ignore any Blitz commands such as 'Use IntuiFont 0'.  I don't =
know the answer off the top of my head, but I think that it is something =
like this -

font_address.l =3D Peek.l(Addr Intuifont(0)+8)

... <setting tags>
scrtag.taglist\l\a =3D #WA_SysFont, font_address

>I'm loading the font into the program and setting it with <Use =
Intuifont> to
>number 0.
>This has the result that all gadgets in the windows are using the =
loaded font.
>But the font of the titlebars (windows and also the screen) are using =
always
>Topaz 8.

When you open the windows, you will be using 'Window' or 'WindowTags'.  =
These commands _will_ take into account 'Use Intuifont x'

>I thought that I must set the parametre #SysFont in the screentaglist =
to
>another number. For instance I load the font to number 1 and use
><scrtag.taglist\l\a=3D#SysFont,1> but it doesn't work...

OS commands usually need a pointer.  So when you are trying to use =
'Intuifont 1' by setting #SysFont to 1, it will actually look for a font =
at the address $00000001 in memory.

Merry Christmas,
Julian Kinraid





@ENDNODE
