Content-Type: text/plain

Hi Andre,

On 21-Dec-97, Andre Beer wrote:
>Here's my question from friday again - hope someone ca help...

>Hi Blitzers!

>Could someone of you explain, you I can set the font of titlebars of windows
>and screens? Look at the following part of my source (not executable):

>  scrtag.taglist\a\a=#LikeWorkbench,False
>  scrtag.taglist\b\a=#Width,\wi
>  ...  <setting tags>
>  scrtag.taglist\l\a=#SysFont,0
>  ...
>  Use IntuiFont 0
>  scree.l=OpenScreenTagList_(False,&scrtag\a\a)
>  ScreenToFront_(&scree)
>  FindScreen 0,Scr
>  Use Screen 0


>Could someone help?

>Thanks in advance.

>Andre

I am not really sure about this, but here is what the AutoDocs says:


        Font = pointer to the default TextAttr structure for text in this 
            screen and all windows that open in this screen.  Text that uses
            this TextAttr includes title bars of both screen and windows,
            string gadgets, and menu titles.  Of course, IntuiText that
            specifies a NULL TextAttr field will use the screen/window default
            fonts.  NOTE: Intuition will *NOT* call OpenDiskFont(), so
            the TextAttr you supply must be in memory.  The ways to ensure
            that are to either use a ROM font (Topaz 8 or 9) or first
            call OpenDiskFont() to load the font, and don't close it
            until after your screen is successfully opened.
            [For V36: this is superseded by SA_Font and SA_SysFont.]

So I would try:

#Font,0  (not #SysFont)

If that doesn't work:

ptr.l=Peek.l(addr Font(0)+8)   ;gives address of font's TextFont struct

then use #Font,&ptr


Also, I think this must be a non-proportional font or the default font will be
used anyway.

Sorry that this is not too clear, but no one else answered, so these ideas
might be worth trying.




-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
