> >> How can I load unsigned bytes from a file ? Because Blitz convert them
> >> each time in format 'signed bytes' (-128 ; 127), and I need a value
> >> beetwen 0 and 255. So I check the sign and change the value if it's
> >> necessary but it's not very efficent.
> >> 
> >Anyway I learnt in class (I actually learnt something at Uni!) last 
> >week that the last BIT of the BYTE holds the sign value.
> 
> >%10000011  = -3
> > ^
> >This BIT, when 1, means the value is a negative (or is it the other 
> >way around).
> 
> In fact this example is WRONG because the negative numbers starts from the
> other end of the hex number. For example:
> 
> %11111111= -1
> %11111110= -2
> %11111101= -3
> %11111100= -4  and so on.
> 
> %10000000= -128 Minumum value in Signed byte
> %01111111= +127 Maximum value in Signed byte

Thats right.
The actual method that most computer systems use for negative numbers
is called 2's Complement.

You can work out the negative of a number by logicaly NOTing it and 
adding 1 to it.  The most significant bit can be seen as the sign 
bit.  A 1 is for minus numbers.

If a calculation floods into this sign bit then the 'Overflow' flag is 
set.  Note: This is different from the 'Carry' flag.

I think all this is correct; i've just had a lesson on it actualy but 
didn't really take it in. This info is more useful if you are putting 
in some assembly, really.
 
