Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

On 10-Dec-97, Budda/Progress wrote:
>> Hello,
>Welcome!

>> How can I load unsigned bytes from a file ? Because Blitz convert them=

>> each time in format 'signed bytes' (-128 ; 127), and I need a value
>> beetwen 0 and 255. So I check the sign and change the value if it's
>> necessary but it's not very efficent.
>> =

>I'm having the same problem and so is my flat mate!  I don't =

>understand the stupidity of it !?!

Read it to WORD type variable and AND it with $ff like this:

result.w=3Dpeek.b(address)&$ff

>Anyway I learnt in class (I actually learnt something at Uni!) last =

>week that the last BIT of the BYTE holds the sign value.

>%10000011  =3D -3
> ^
>This BIT, when 1, means the value is a negative (or is it the other =

>way around).

In fact this example is WRONG because the negative numbers starts from th=
e
other end of the hex number. For example:

%11111111=3D -1
%11111110=3D -2
%11111101=3D -3
%11111100=3D -4  and so on.

%10000000=3D -128 Minumum value in Signed byte
%01111111=3D +127 Maximum value in Signed byte

