Received: from fpgapc16.essex.ac.uk by seralph10.essex.ac.uk; (5.65v3.2/1.1.8.2/14Feb95-1154AM)
	id AA26366; Fri, 19 Dec 1997 18:49:34 GMT
From: C Dimitrakakis <cdimita@essex.ac.uk>
To: blitz-list <blitz-list%netsoc.ucd.ie@uk.ac.essex.mailhost>
Subject: Re: Stoping Sound Samples
In-Reply-To: <yam7290.4.4696864@smtp.ix.netcom.com>
Message-Id: <SIMEON.9712191801.E@fpgapc16.essex.ac.uk>
Date: Fri, 19 Dec 1997 18:50:01 +0000 (GMT)
Priority: NORMAL
X-Mailer: Simeon for Win32 Version 4.1.2 Build (32)
X-Authentication: IMSP
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; CHARSET=US-ASCII


On Wed, 17 Dec 1997 21:14:00 -0600 Curt Esser 
<camge%ix.netcom.com@uk.ac.essex.mailhost> wrote:

> Hi,
> 
> On 17-Dec-97, Daniel Allsopp wrote:
> >Hi,
> >   Does anyone know how to stop a sound from playing, after it's started
> >playing using the Sound command??
>

do
MOVE.w (%dcba)|#dma_clr,#DMACON
to stop some channels
ie

MOVE.w #dma_clr|(%0100),#DMACON 	to stop channel c

to start them again use:

MOVE.w (%dcba)|#dma_set,#DMACON

#dma_clr is 0, so you dont need to put that, but I put it there
to make the code more readable:?)

#dma_set is the highest bit of the DMACON register set to 1,
so it is equal to 32768(=%1000000000000000)

so you actually write
%000000000000dcba to clear individual audio dma bits
%100000000000dcba to set individual audio dma bits

don`t try to set/clr any other bits (the ones which I indicate as 0 
always), as those are other dma bits (blitter,copper...) and you`d fuck 
everything up most probably if you change them randomly :)



Christos Dimitrakakis (aka Olethros)
Electronic Engineer,
Software Developer for the Amiga computer
University of Essex
http://esewww.essex.ac.uk/~cdimita



@ENDNODE
