Organization: Diverse
Subject: Re: Strings
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

On 21-Dec-97, Dave wrote:
>    Can anyone explain how strings work from an asm point of
>    view. How are they set out in memory? like a linked list?

Strings are just bytes in memory and usually pointed using LONG pointer t=
o
the start of the string. In blitz the length of string is the previous LO=
Ng
from the first character in the string.

Memory::..

dc.l n; This longword holds the length of the following string
dc.b "this text is like strings in blitz"
blk.b m,0 ; And here is m empty bytes for the string to grow, if
;  needed to.

dc.l k; Next strings length
dc.b "text"; The next string in memory

and so on.


Hope this explain that to you?

         _____________________________________________________
