> ;  needed to.

  Well this is what I thought but I remember someone saying that
  if they tried to save the string by taking the address plus length
  and storing that, when they tried to load this back in it was corrupt.
  Someone said to this that the memory for the string wouldn`t have been
  allocated properly. This is why I thought it might be more like a
linked
  list.
  Also when watching the REDDubbugger it displays how long a string is
and
  it`s maxium length, when adding more to a string if there isn`t
enought
  room the maxium length gets bigger. If the example above is correct
then
  a bigger block of memory must be allocated and the string moved to
that
  block of memory , Yes or no?
  In the above example how does blitz know how much empty bytes to leave
  for the string to grow?  This can`t be worked out at compile time can
it?


Thank for the help

