In-Reply-To: <tcppop3.2365646@rockford.com>
X-Mailer: YAM 1.3.4 - Amiga Mailer by Marcel Beck
Organization: Blip!
Subject: Re: Taking Offense
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

On 11-Dec-97, comunion@plmorris.demon.co.uk wrote:

>On 10-Dec-97, bal / what? / progress / fuckoff . iff Blurted out:
>>>Damn, its been done before!  I thought I had a new idea.

> Hmmmmmm...Can u keep the Offensive Language to a Minimum Please .
>Im sure everyone on this list does not want to find Offensive Language i=
n
>there MAIL BOX . I hope you read This !

>Cheers , Paul

I hate to be a pain here, but I had to reply to this message.

Personally, I am not offended in the least when someone uses the word
"damn" or "fuck."  I occasionally use these words myself.  In fact,
you might very well be the _only_ person on this list who was offended
by the use of these words.

(I will admit that the use of the word "fuck" in email is rather
unprofessional, but we're a bunch of fun lovin' folk, right?)

If you truly had a problem with his using the words "damn" or =

"fuck," perhaps it would have been a better tactic to reply to him in
private email rather than by replying to the list.  Replying to the =

list makes all the hundreds of people who subscribe to this list have =

to download your 1K message complaining about the inconsequential use
of such words.  =


Would you like to know what _does_ offend me?  I'll tell you.

a)  People who do not know how to correctly use grammar or punctuation
b)  People who tag 18-line auto-signatures to 4-line messages
c)  People who forward Microsoft jokes to a mailing list that contains
    over a hundred subscribers and carries over 70 messages a day
d)  People who are offended by the word "damn"

I don't mind having the word "damn" in a message in my mailbox.  I
see much more worse things in my mailbox -- namely, advertisements for
netsex sites or messages containing poorly-punctuated jibberish that
looks as if it was written by a second grader.

Case in point:

> Hmmmmmm...Can u keep the Offensive Language to a Minimum Please .

What is this?  I've never heard of the word "u".  I also didn't know
that people using the English language capitalized simple nouns and
adjectives within sentences.  Oh, and maybe I'm mistaken, but I also
believe that when someone is asking a question, they are to use a
_question mark_ rather than a _period_.  A question mark looks like
this: ?

Perhaps this sentence should read:

"Hmmmm... Can you keep the offensive language to a minimum please?"

>Im sure everyone on this list does not want to find Offensive Language i=
n

I've also never seen the word "Im" before.  Maybe the author is attemptin=
g
to use the contraction of "I am."  In this case, the correct contraction
would contain an _apostrophe_.  An apostrophe looks like this: '

Let's see the corrected sentence.

"I'm sure everyone on this list does not want to find offensive language =
in"

Ahh, much better.  Let's continue.

>there MAIL BOX . I hope you read This !

"there MAIL BOX?"  Is this a colloquial representation of Shakespeare
of old in which an actor may perhaps say, "That light upon which YONDER
MAIL BOX doth break?"  No, probably not.  The author is most likely
referring to the possessive term "their."  I also have never read any
books in which the sentences are separated by two spaces and a
punctuation mark.  Usually, there is the punctuation mark and then
two spaces.  It may be that the author meant this line to look like
this:

"their MAIL BOX.  I hope you read this!"

Hopefully someone may learn something from my short lesson and put
these words to use next time he or she posts to the Blitz List.

Love,
Tim

(I do not wish to start a "flame war," but if you desire to, please
keep it off of this list.  If you must make a public rebuttal, then
do so, but any further conversation must take place via private
email.)

-- =


