   Yes, that wasn't "real" code, but rather a "model" just to illustrate
   the basic principles.  At any rate, you have sorted it out (there are
   a few ways of actually implementing it), so well done!!


> As when some small bobs come along I can fill all 3 buffers and
> my code sometimes overwrote the visible buffer.

   Yep, that's the problem... it can run way too quickly when the
   number of bobs drop, but all you need to do is check if your
   working bitmap = the visible bitmap and either hold for a bit or
   you could try changing the working bitmap (and skipping ahead a
   frame)...

   If Hidden=visible
      Hidden=QWrap(Hidden+2,0,3)
   EndIf
 
   I'm not sure how you're handling it, but it looks like you're running
   off the "test"-code I posted here. In my own demo, I display the
   new bitmap like this...

   DisplayBitmap coplist,QWrap(Hidden-1,0,3)

   
> I might even upgrade it to quadruple buffering to save this wasted
> time =)

   Haha... getting a bit carried away, aren't you?!  More power to you,
   when it comes to maxxing out your frame-rate all is fair...

   Quadruple-buffering might get around the problem, although the
   delay between player-input and the visible-result will be delayed a
   bit more, it shouldn't increase too much.


