Received: (qmail 29600 invoked by alias); 12 Dec 1997 11:48:37 -0000
Mailing-List: contact blitz-list-help@netsoc.ucd.ie; run by ezmlm
Delivered-To: mailing list blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie
Received: (qmail 29595 invoked from network); 12 Dec 1997 11:48:36 -0000
Received: from sosbbs.com (HELO mailhost.sosbbs.com) (204.186.168.100)
  by orca.ucd.ie with SMTP; 12 Dec 1997 11:48:36 -0000
Received: from gbenjam (204.186.168.57) by mailhost.sosbbs.com
 (EMWAC SMTPRS 0.81) with SMTP id <B0000156903@mailhost.sosbbs.com>;
 Fri, 12 Dec 1997 06:47:08 -0500
Message-ID: <B0000156903@mailhost.sosbbs.com>
From: "Garfield Benjamin" <gbenjam@sosbbs.com>
To: "BLITZ MAILING LIST" <blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
Subject: Triple Buffering (was Re:Screen Double Buffering??)
Date: Fri, 12 Dec 1997 06:54:45 -0500
X-MSMail-Priority: Normal
X-Priority: 3
X-Mailer: Microsoft Internet Mail 4.70.1155
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

>  But if the screen redraws are synched to an interrupt which occurs 
> every VBL, then you will drop back to 30fps, if you use the example 
> code that was posted a few msgs ago, because new frames are only 
> shown once they are rendered, so if 1 frame goes over 1 VBL, then the 
> next frame won't be shown until the end of the 2nd, effectively 
> reducing your frame rate to 30fps.

   That code I threw up here was just a general "sketch" to try to
   illustrate the basic design. It might appear that you will drop back to
   the next frame-rate, but in practice you don't.

   Okay, let me clear up some of the issues...

   Let me point out that I'm certainly not saying triple-buffering is the
   only way to boost your program speed, nor am I saying it's perfect...

   There are two benefits from using triple-buffering:

   First, since you are no longer relying on a VWait in your main loop,
   you are gaining more time to process code and draw gfx which 
   translates into a few more objects on-screen in 1 Vbl.

   However, everything has it's limit and so you might have so many
   objects to process and draw that it's impossible to update and draw
   them all within 1Vbl.  Perhaps, you have dropped from 50fps to 45fps.

   Okay, here's where it gets interesting... with a double-buffering
   system, there is no 45fps and your program drops from 50fps down
   to 25fps, even though technically it's capable of running at 45fps.

   Now, with triple-buffering, you have one bitmap being viewed, one
   bitmap fully rendered (which will be displayed at the next Vbl-
   interrupt) and a third bitmap you are rendering right "now".

   So, even if you drop to 45fps, the display will still be updated at
   50fps as you already have the next frame fully rendered and are
   working on the one after that.  Basically, you can consider that you
   are always two frames ahead which allows you to update at max
   frame-rate even though the actual loop-rate might drop below 50fps. 

   I hope this clears up some of the confusion... it's not perfect, but it
   is an interesting method to gain a bit more performance and the
   best part is that it's non-platform dependant meaning you can apply
   it on the Amiga as well as the IBMclones (where it is most-used)...

   I don't know how to explain it any better than the above.  As I said
   in my last message, I can send the source for a simple demo 
   which illustrates the advantages of triple-buffering over double-
   buffering and that's probably the best way as you can simply run the
   demo and see that it actually does work.

   It was a bit tricky to get it to synchronize correctly in BLITZ's
   SetInt5 method, but it does work flawlessly on my machine.  It 
   would be interesting to see how it performs on slower and faster
   machines.  I'm running it on a 14MHz A1200 w/8MBFastRAM.
 

      Take  care,   
      GARFIELD
      _________________________
      Current projects...
      SideShooter(AMOS): 94% Complete
      Website(http://www.sosbbs.com/~gbenjam): 20% Complete


@ENDNODE
