From: Andrew Kennan <bewilder@coastlink.com.au>
Reply-To: bewilder@coastlink.com.au
To: blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie
Date: Tue, 02 Dec 1997 22:44:58 +0800
Message-ID: <yam7275.2915.123346496@coastlink.com.au>
X-Mailer: YAM 1.3.4 [020] - Amiga Mailer by Marcel Beck
Organization: NCLI
Subject: Visual Blitz
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

Hi
This VisualBlitz idea sounds pretty nifty. I have a couple of
questions/statements to make. :]

Aren't the various "Visual" type packages (Visual Basic, C++, J++, Delphi,
etc) based around object oriented languages? Will the proposed Visual Blitz
system provide an aparently object oriented front end to the Blitz language?
What I mean by this is, will VBlitz provide a bunch of Methods for each
object? 

eg. You have a window which contains two buttons and a string gadget. Press
each button and they will put some text in the string gadget.

Your Visual Blitz code looks like this:

   Function Win_1_CloseGadget{}
      Quit
   End Function

   Function Button_1_Click{}
      String_1.Text = "You pressed Button 1"
   End Function

   Function Button_2_Click{}
      String_1.Text = "You pressed Button 2"
   End Function

But the Blitz code it outputs will look like this:

**** Start Of Example

*initialise window, buttons and string gadget etc*

#VB_CloseWindow = $200   ; Visual Blitz declares constants for gadget handling
etc
#VB_GadgetUp = $100

VB_Quit.b = False  ; Built in Visual Blitz variables
VB_ev.l = 0 
VB_ew.l = 0
VB_gh.l = 0
dump.l = 0

; *** Functions For Win_1 

Function.l Win_1_CloseGadget{}
   Shared VB_Quit
   VB_Quit = True
End Function

; *** Functions For Button_1 of Win_1

Function.l Button_1_Click{}
   GTSetString 1,3,"You pressed Button 1"
End Function

; *** Functions For Button_2 of Win_1

Function.l Button_2_Click{}
   GTSetString 1,3,"You Pressed Button 2"
End Function

; *** Main Loop

While VB_Quit = False

   delay_(1)
   VB_ev = Event
   VB_ew = EventWindow

   Select VB_ew
      Case 1
         Select VB_ev

            Case #VB_GadgetUp
               VB_gh = GadgetHit

               Select VB_gh

                  Case 1
                     dump = Win_1_Button_1_Click{}

                  Case 2
                     dump = Win_1_Button_2_Click{}

               End Select
   
            Case #VB_WindowClosed
               dump = Win_1_CloseGadget{}

         End Select

   End Select
Wend

* Clean  up *
End

**** End Of Example

Don't expect my example to be perfect :] I wrote it off the top of my head.
It's just an illustration of what I imagine Visual Blitz to be for.

I think Visual Blitz has the potential to be a powerful and easy software
development tool. The code it produces will be bigger and slower than normal
"hand written" code but if the output from Visual Blitz is easy to understand
there should be nothing stopping a competent coder optimising the program. It
will seriously improve the amount of time it takes to create a GUI and will
reduce the number of errors in coding.

A while ago I was considering writing a set of functions which would allow me
to easily resize a GadTools GUI. I find the fixed size of most GadTools GUIs
very annoying. A section of code that resizes the objects of a GTList when the
window is resized would be a very useful inclusion into Visual Blitz. The
VBlitz programmer would not even need to know about it, it would be
implemented automatically.

Also! Automatic use of the Commodity system (a la MUI) and perhaps
AppIcons/Windows/Menu Items could be made automatic or at least very easily
implemented eg a Property of a window could be that it is an AppWindow. The
ability to "Iconify" any program would also be handy. How cool would it be to
have a command called Iconify which could be attached to a button or a menu
item? When it is called, all the windows close and an appicon is created and
the program waits till it is woken up at which point it returns to where it
was before.

I may have just complicated matters a lot. But I believe features like these
(and more!) would really make Visual Blitz a kick-arse application and a truly
useful development tool. I would be glad to take part in this project if I'm
wanted/needed :]

Seeya
Andrew
-- 
