Subject: Re: Will Microsoft Die B4 the end of the Millenium?
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain

Hi C, On 17-Dec-97 you wrote...

>BTW, did you know that Microsoft now issues 'Degrees' of some sort?
>Yes, they do.

>They award 'Qualified Microsoft Engineer' awards/degrees to people 
>passing some particular M$ tests...

>The sad thing is that people are actually taking the tests :(

You would too if it could increase your salary and job security. A Microsoft
Engineer can earn a lot of cash.

>Next thing will be M$ University (MsTM)

It will be called Cambridge98 :) They already sponsor a research wing there,
and we all know what happens when M$ buy a stake in a sucessful business.

>I hope Netscape and Sun teach them a lesson.

Why not, it's about time they gave then some knowledge back. Both of these
companies have learnt a hell of a lot from Microsoft and want to be in
exactly the same position.
Did you know that Navigator does not support standard java, and that it is
starting to look like an operating system itself.
If java becomes standard, do not expect most java apps to run on an Amiga at
any decent speed if at all. Java also is trying to become an operating system,
that will most likely have more in common with windoze95 than Amiga o/s or
UNIX.
Sun Microsystems will *control* Java and users will be dependant on them for
language/system updates.

Maybe I'm being cynical, but I would like something really cool to take down
Microsoft. Like the Amiga :))

bye.
-- 
Matt Daniels
mattd@underused.u-net.com



@ENDNODE
