Subject: Re: [Blitz] Registration & Tooltypes
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain


Hi Paul,

On 06-Dec-97, Paul Anderton wrote:
>Hi Guys and Guyesses!

>Chapter 1 - I have in my hand a piece of paper...

>I`ve been noticing a lot of stuff about the UK blitz distributors.
>Guildhall leisure aren't able to help, and Red when Excited seem
>to have taken over...

>The thing is, where does this leave me and my registration card?

As far as my experience goes, you may as well file it in your own round file
and save the postage.  I sent my registration and money for a BUM subscription
when I first got Blitz, at version 1.7   I never recieved anything in return. 
To get an update I finally bought Version 2.1   I also sent the registration
card in for this to the specified address (smart enough this time to send no
money, though) and again got nothing back.

>Chapter 2 - Take a letter, Miss Tool...

>I was wondering about tooltypes. Is there an EASY way to send
>parameters via tooltypes to my program? I tried (but I failed) to
>use that parameter thingy (I've been off the Mig for a couple of
>weeks - you should see my mail folder. The other man-made object
>visible from space!), and if I can't use tooltypes, I'll have to use a
>prefs file, which would be a bit excessive, as the program is quite
>small!

Check your RITooltypesLib doc for information on how to read the tooltypes. 
I've never used this, but it should do what you want.

I have use the NumPars thing before, and it seems to work OK.  It will tell
your program the name of the project that called it.  I use this to let people
use a different language by clicking on the "English", or "German", or
whatever icon.  Then the main program knows which language file to use.  I
could send you an example for this if you want.


>Any help with either of these would be appreciated muchly @:-)=

>TTFN

>Paul "E" Babes

>-- 
>You have been reading...
>paul@ebabes.mersinet.co.uk

>"I Think therefore I am"
>                                    French philosophy

>"All that can be thought is not true"
>                                    Hindu philosophy

"I don't know what to think of this! :)"
                                     Curt's philosophy 


-- 
                                            Yours electronically,
                                            Curt Esser
                                            camge@ix.netcom.com



@ENDNODE
